1
00:00:14,014 --> 00:00:18,151
A makeover project
for your most unhinged leftovers.

2
00:00:18,218 --> 00:00:21,688
The best chefs in Korea will
turn your fridge inside out.

3
00:00:21,755 --> 00:00:23,857
The classy cooking show has returned.

4
00:00:23,923 --> 00:00:26,426
-<i>Chef & My Fridge</i>!
-<i>My Fridge</i>!

5
00:00:28,962 --> 00:00:31,831
-It's nice to see you.
-Welcome, chefs.

6
00:00:31,898 --> 00:00:36,036
We're continuing the battle between
the returning chefs and the new chefs.

7
00:00:36,102 --> 00:00:39,439
<i>Last week,</i>
<i>the match ended in a tie, two to two.</i>

8
00:00:39,506 --> 00:00:44,577
The returning chefs are still in the lead
with one win and two ties.

9
00:00:44,644 --> 00:00:48,281
I think it was about time
the new chefs stopped challenging them.

10
00:00:48,348 --> 00:00:50,850
They've tried enough. But you know,

11
00:00:50,917 --> 00:00:55,855
this man returned to Korea
after another 15-hour flight.

12
00:00:55,922 --> 00:00:57,757
We're doing it once again because of him.

13
00:00:57,824 --> 00:01:00,293
-It's Chef Kyun.
-Yes.

14
00:01:00,360 --> 00:01:01,995
When did you arrive, Chef Kyun?

15
00:01:02,062 --> 00:01:03,963
-I came last week.
-Last week.

16
00:01:04,030 --> 00:01:06,900
I got a good sleep, and I came prepared.

17
00:01:06,966 --> 00:01:09,869
He must've analyzed the cause of loss
after the previous episode

18
00:01:09,936 --> 00:01:11,071
and realized he was tired.

19
00:01:11,137 --> 00:01:13,573
-He yawned during the shoot,
-He did.

20
00:01:13,640 --> 00:01:15,675
<i>-and even dozed off too.</i>
<i>-Right.</i>

21
00:01:15,742 --> 00:01:18,111
After I returned to America,

22
00:01:18,178 --> 00:01:21,214
I became the 15-minute man.

23
00:01:21,281 --> 00:01:22,282
The 15-minute man.

24
00:01:22,348 --> 00:01:24,884
You've become the 15-minute man?
The 15-minute man?

25
00:01:24,951 --> 00:01:27,821
I do everything at home in 15 minutes.

26
00:01:28,388 --> 00:01:31,357
-I made breakfast in 15 minutes.
-In 15 minutes.

27
00:01:31,424 --> 00:01:33,660
-I took naps for 15 minutes.
-For 15 minutes.

28
00:01:33,726 --> 00:01:35,361
-And your showers?
-For 15 minutes.

29
00:01:35,428 --> 00:01:38,465
-He turned his life into 15 minutes.
-Everything that he does.

30
00:01:38,531 --> 00:01:40,633
-Everything.
-Everything was in 15 minutes.

31
00:01:40,700 --> 00:01:41,701
That's frightening.

32
00:01:41,768 --> 00:01:43,036
Did you miss your friend?

33
00:01:43,103 --> 00:01:46,372
-Yes, the Year of the Mouse.
-That's us. The same year.

34
00:01:46,439 --> 00:01:49,809
Speaking of which, Chef Hyun-suk
had been here all along, but not today.

35
00:01:49,876 --> 00:01:52,946
Yes, today, Baby Choi Hyun-suk sits

36
00:01:53,012 --> 00:01:55,315
-in Chef Hyun-suk's seat.
-Right.

37
00:01:55,381 --> 00:01:56,950
-Baby Hyun-suk.
-Yes.

38
00:01:57,016 --> 00:01:59,519
-We have similar images…
-Yes?

39
00:01:59,586 --> 00:02:01,621
-…so only one of us is enough.
-I see.

40
00:02:01,688 --> 00:02:03,423
-You're the fresh Hyun-suk.
-Right.

41
00:02:03,490 --> 00:02:05,992
-He's fresh.
-Fresh Hyun-suk.

42
00:02:06,059 --> 00:02:09,229
Anyway, Chef Kang-rok.
The color of your cap has changed.

43
00:02:09,295 --> 00:02:10,864
-Right?
-You're right.

44
00:02:10,930 --> 00:02:12,198
Was there a change of heart?

45
00:02:13,466 --> 00:02:14,701
I crossed over to the dark side.

46
00:02:15,268 --> 00:02:16,302
EVEN DARK KANG-ROK IS SHY

47
00:02:16,369 --> 00:02:17,570
Most people get a haircut

48
00:02:17,637 --> 00:02:19,672
-when they have a change of heart.
-Right.

49
00:02:19,739 --> 00:02:21,274
-His cap.
-He changed his cap.

50
00:02:21,341 --> 00:02:24,010
-I'll put in everything I have.
-Everything he has.

51
00:02:24,077 --> 00:02:27,447
What about becoming the third chef
from your captain's seat?

52
00:02:27,514 --> 00:02:29,482
-It's wonderful.
-I knew it.

53
00:02:29,549 --> 00:02:30,550
Do you prefer that seat?

54
00:02:30,617 --> 00:02:33,353
-Please come by often.
-"Please come by often."

55
00:02:33,419 --> 00:02:36,122
But two seats was a little harsh.

56
00:02:36,189 --> 00:02:38,925
-He's two seats down.
-Just one would be enough.

57
00:02:38,992 --> 00:02:42,462
Chef Jong-won, how did people respond
to your appearance on the show?

58
00:02:42,529 --> 00:02:44,964
My restaurant was mentioned here,

59
00:02:45,031 --> 00:02:46,399
-so my team was excited.
-Your team.

60
00:02:46,466 --> 00:02:49,035
When I first told them
I'd be appearing on the show,

61
00:02:49,102 --> 00:02:51,671
they told me to relax
and not focus on winning.

62
00:02:51,738 --> 00:02:54,841
<i>But they were very happy</i>
<i>that I won and got a star.</i>

63
00:02:54,908 --> 00:02:58,845
They were as happy as the time
when we received the Michelin star.

64
00:02:58,912 --> 00:03:00,413
You were chosen by Won-young

65
00:03:00,480 --> 00:03:01,681
-and won against Chef Sam.
-He did.

66
00:03:01,748 --> 00:03:04,350
-That's pretty huge.
-And at once.

67
00:03:04,417 --> 00:03:08,788
Today, amazing actors
have come to <i>Chef & My Fridge</i>.

68
00:03:08,855 --> 00:03:10,823
Let's find out who they are.

69
00:03:10,890 --> 00:03:13,459
Please welcome them. Come on out!

70
00:03:13,526 --> 00:03:15,662
These are the fridge owners.

71
00:03:16,296 --> 00:03:18,464
They're walking out.

72
00:03:18,531 --> 00:03:19,899
Welcome.

73
00:03:20,867 --> 00:03:24,504
-They're walking out.
-Welcome.

74
00:03:24,571 --> 00:03:25,738
They're today's fridge owners.

75
00:03:25,805 --> 00:03:29,142
Please welcome actors with a twist,
Hyun Bong-sik and Son Suk-ku!

76
00:03:29,209 --> 00:03:30,777
Welcome.

77
00:03:32,612 --> 00:03:34,347
I revere you.

78
00:03:34,414 --> 00:03:36,049
Beat it if you're done watching.

79
00:03:36,115 --> 00:03:38,918
<i>From a frightening villain</i>
<i>of </i>The Roundup <i>franchise</i>

80
00:03:38,985 --> 00:03:41,888
<i>to Mr. Gu whom you'll end up revering,</i>

81
00:03:42,956 --> 00:03:45,291
-<i>an actor with two extreme charms…</i>
-Salute.

82
00:03:45,959 --> 00:03:48,194
Have you checked on everyone?

83
00:03:48,828 --> 00:03:50,630
…please welcome Son Suk-ku!

84
00:03:50,697 --> 00:03:53,533
-It's nice to be here.
-Welcome to the show, Suk-ku.

85
00:03:54,334 --> 00:03:55,702
Thank you for inviting me.

86
00:03:55,768 --> 00:03:58,171
Hello, viewers. My name is Son Suk-ku.

87
00:03:58,238 --> 00:03:59,305
Thank you…

88
00:03:59,372 --> 00:04:00,940
HESITANT

89
00:04:02,342 --> 00:04:05,278
Well, the viewers didn't invite me.

90
00:04:05,345 --> 00:04:07,413
It's as good as that.

91
00:04:07,480 --> 00:04:10,116
-Thank you for inviting me.
-Yes.

92
00:04:11,851 --> 00:04:13,886
Are you blaming the failure on me?

93
00:04:13,953 --> 00:04:15,855
Please give me a call at your convenience.

94
00:04:15,922 --> 00:04:17,257
Look at the death.

95
00:04:17,323 --> 00:04:18,758
You'll end up dying.

96
00:04:18,825 --> 00:04:20,793
It's the most recent hairstyle.

97
00:04:21,427 --> 00:04:25,331
<i>He's an actor with a significant presence</i>
<i>in many different works,</i>

98
00:04:25,398 --> 00:04:28,835
but in reality, he's known
as the cutie-pie Lovely Bong.

99
00:04:28,901 --> 00:04:31,037
Please welcome Hyun Bong-sik!

100
00:04:31,104 --> 00:04:32,305
Welcome to the show.

101
00:04:32,372 --> 00:04:34,540
-It's great to have you.
-Nice to meet you.

102
00:04:34,607 --> 00:04:37,644
I heard you enjoy watching
<i>Chef & My Fridge</i>, Suk-ku.

103
00:04:37,710 --> 00:04:39,912
I've been a fan for a long time,

104
00:04:39,979 --> 00:04:41,748
and I loved <i>Culinary Class Wars </i>too.

105
00:04:41,814 --> 00:04:45,385
-That's why we came dressed in black.
-Yes.

106
00:04:45,451 --> 00:04:47,620
-We talked about it beforehand.
-I see.

107
00:04:47,687 --> 00:04:49,422
He's showing that respect.

108
00:04:49,489 --> 00:04:52,458
And Chef Edward, who's next to me now,

109
00:04:52,525 --> 00:04:55,728
moved me deeply
during <i>Culinary Class Wars</i>.

110
00:04:55,795 --> 00:04:58,598
It's the fact that he had a huge career

111
00:04:58,665 --> 00:05:01,100
and was still willing to participate
in a competition,

112
00:05:01,167 --> 00:05:04,504
<i>-although he could always choose safety.</i>
<i>-Right.</i>

113
00:05:04,570 --> 00:05:07,073
<i>I saw him continuously choosing</i>
<i>challenges instead.</i>

114
00:05:07,140 --> 00:05:09,475
I began to wonder
if I could do what he did.

115
00:05:09,542 --> 00:05:11,144
Thank you.

116
00:05:11,210 --> 00:05:13,413
I see. Yes.

117
00:05:13,479 --> 00:05:17,617
Bong-sik, was there a chef
you wanted to meet?

118
00:05:17,684 --> 00:05:20,053
I thought Chef Kang-rok was
quite similar to me.

119
00:05:20,119 --> 00:05:23,122
-Choi Kang-rok.
-Choi Kang-rok.

120
00:05:23,189 --> 00:05:25,692
He seemed introverted, just like me.

121
00:05:25,758 --> 00:05:28,461
I found out he was an introvert
for the first time today.

122
00:05:28,528 --> 00:05:29,696
Do you call him Bong-sik?

123
00:05:29,762 --> 00:05:32,565
Yes, he's a year older than me.

124
00:05:32,632 --> 00:05:34,067
You're older than him?

125
00:05:34,133 --> 00:05:35,935
-I was born in 1983.
-And I, 1984.

126
00:05:36,002 --> 00:05:37,003
Is that so?

127
00:05:37,070 --> 00:05:39,038
-You were born in 1984?
-You were?

128
00:05:39,105 --> 00:05:40,306
-The Year of the Mouse?
-Yes.

129
00:05:40,373 --> 00:05:42,175
-Twelve years.
-He's twelve years younger.

130
00:05:42,241 --> 00:05:43,943
-He's younger by 12 years.
-My friend.

131
00:05:44,010 --> 00:05:45,244
-You're a mouse?
-Yes.

132
00:05:45,311 --> 00:05:46,979
I'm a mouse too.

133
00:05:47,046 --> 00:05:48,448
-What's going on?
-I see.

134
00:05:48,514 --> 00:05:49,916
-You were born in 1984?
-I was.

135
00:05:49,982 --> 00:05:51,384
You two are the same age.

136
00:05:51,451 --> 00:05:53,353
You two should meet each other.

137
00:05:55,421 --> 00:05:57,924
-It's nice to meet you, friend.
-Hello, friend.

138
00:05:57,990 --> 00:05:59,492
THE MICE FRIENDS

139
00:05:59,559 --> 00:06:00,560
They feel so awkward.

140
00:06:00,626 --> 00:06:05,198
Anyway, there were many chefs
who were dying to meet Suk-ku.

141
00:06:05,264 --> 00:06:06,599
They really wanted to meet him.

142
00:06:06,666 --> 00:06:08,768
Yes, I'm a huge fan.

143
00:06:08,835 --> 00:06:10,436
I see. In which work?

144
00:06:10,503 --> 00:06:11,838
I thought you were

145
00:06:11,904 --> 00:06:15,875
the best villain in <i>The Roundup</i> franchise.

146
00:06:15,942 --> 00:06:17,577
-Kang Hae-sang.
-The villain.

147
00:06:17,643 --> 00:06:20,346
I analyzed the reason

148
00:06:20,413 --> 00:06:24,584
and realized he was born with those eyes.

149
00:06:24,650 --> 00:06:26,886
His eyes were like
murals from the Joseon era.

150
00:06:26,953 --> 00:06:29,689
-Murals from the Joseon era? Which one?
-The Joseon era?

151
00:06:29,756 --> 00:06:31,724
-Murals from the Joseon era?
-If you look at it,

152
00:06:31,791 --> 00:06:35,228
the women in those drawings
do not have double eyelids.

153
00:06:35,294 --> 00:06:37,497
-His key feature.
-His acting comes from his eyes?

154
00:06:37,563 --> 00:06:39,265
No, not his eyes, his eyelids.

155
00:06:39,332 --> 00:06:41,567
-The way they look.
-The eyelids, not the eyes.

156
00:06:41,634 --> 00:06:46,038
-The eyelids.
-Those eyelids help him play good roles

157
00:06:46,105 --> 00:06:50,376
as well as villains,
so they're quite functional.

158
00:06:50,443 --> 00:06:51,944
That was Chef Kang-rok's analysis.

159
00:06:52,011 --> 00:06:54,080
This was the first time

160
00:06:54,147 --> 00:06:56,949
anyone has complimented me on my eyelids.

161
00:06:58,785 --> 00:07:00,853
I've never heard
such detailed compliment before.

162
00:07:00,920 --> 00:07:02,522
-You were great.
-Thank you.

163
00:07:02,588 --> 00:07:05,425
That was the longest
Kang-rok has spoken on the show.

164
00:07:05,491 --> 00:07:07,393
-That was a speech.
-That was long.

165
00:07:07,460 --> 00:07:08,561
It means he's a real fan.

166
00:07:08,628 --> 00:07:10,630
-That's all.
-That's right. He usually gets quiet

167
00:07:10,696 --> 00:07:12,331
-when someone refutes him.
-Right.

168
00:07:12,398 --> 00:07:17,503
Suk-ku had a reason
for visiting <i>Chef & My Fridge</i> today.

169
00:07:17,570 --> 00:07:20,440
I'll appear on a JTBC drama series

170
00:07:20,506 --> 00:07:23,376
titled <i>More Beautiful Than Paradise</i>.

171
00:07:23,443 --> 00:07:27,613
<i>It's the love story of a couple</i>
<i>who have reached their latter years.</i>

172
00:07:28,214 --> 00:07:31,551
I'm playing Ms. Kim Hye-ja's husband.

173
00:07:31,617 --> 00:07:34,787
-Ms. Kim Hye-ja's husband?
-I'm her husband.

174
00:07:34,854 --> 00:07:36,923
-What?
-When I stop there,

175
00:07:36,989 --> 00:07:39,525
-people get confused and go, "What?"
-Yes.

176
00:07:39,592 --> 00:07:41,561
-The age gap isn't that big.
-No, right?

177
00:07:41,627 --> 00:07:45,131
-Even if she was older, she'd be too old.
-It's a bit of a stretch.

178
00:07:45,198 --> 00:07:49,302
Hae-suk, played by Ms. Kim,
passes away and goes to paradise.

179
00:07:49,368 --> 00:07:51,237
<i>You're now in paradise.</i>

180
00:07:51,304 --> 00:07:52,405
<i>I'm in paradise?</i>

181
00:07:52,472 --> 00:07:54,974
<i>The community center in paradise</i>
<i>asks her a question.</i>

182
00:07:55,041 --> 00:07:57,577
How old do you wish to look
as you live in paradise?

183
00:07:57,643 --> 00:08:03,683
My dear wife,
you're the prettiest right now.

184
00:08:03,749 --> 00:08:04,884
Eighty.

185
00:08:04,951 --> 00:08:06,285
You want to be 80 again?

186
00:08:06,352 --> 00:08:07,620
HIS WORDS MADE HER LIVE AS 80

187
00:08:07,687 --> 00:08:11,691
But I had returned to my mid-thirties
all by myself.

188
00:08:11,757 --> 00:08:13,192
Goodness, honey.

189
00:08:13,259 --> 00:08:14,861
THE COUPLE REUNITE IN PARADISE

190
00:08:14,927 --> 00:08:16,229
I'm screwed.

191
00:08:17,163 --> 00:08:19,265
How is this paradise?

192
00:08:19,332 --> 00:08:22,502
Everyone is living their best life now,
but you're here as an old woman!

193
00:08:22,568 --> 00:08:25,972
<i>The story is about what happens</i>
<i>as the couple live in paradise.</i>

194
00:08:26,038 --> 00:08:28,407
-That's a fun setting.
-Isn't it interesting?

195
00:08:28,474 --> 00:08:30,409
I wish such paradise exists.

196
00:08:30,476 --> 00:08:33,379
I heard Ms. Kim

197
00:08:33,446 --> 00:08:36,682
singled out Suk-ku
and wanted him as her partner.

198
00:08:36,749 --> 00:08:37,950
Is this true?

199
00:08:38,017 --> 00:08:42,688
At that time, I was searching for a work
that'd be the most romantic in history,

200
00:08:42,755 --> 00:08:44,524
-so I was trying to find one.
-Yes, I see.

201
00:08:44,590 --> 00:08:49,529
And the director asked whom she thought
would be fitting as her male partner.

202
00:08:49,595 --> 00:08:51,030
And she said,

203
00:08:51,097 --> 00:08:55,935
"I liked that guy who played Mr. Gu
in <i>My Liberation Notes</i>."

204
00:08:57,803 --> 00:09:02,475
The production was an experience
I'd never get to live again

205
00:09:02,542 --> 00:09:05,177
for the rest of my life.

206
00:09:05,244 --> 00:09:08,514
Above all,
I thought the chemistry between her and me

207
00:09:08,581 --> 00:09:10,316
was the real deal.

208
00:09:10,383 --> 00:09:14,687
You'll be able to watch our chemistry
that transcends generations and age.

209
00:09:14,754 --> 00:09:16,589
Around what time will it get aired?

210
00:09:16,656 --> 00:09:18,558
I'm not sure.

211
00:09:19,692 --> 00:09:21,160
-When will it begin?
-I don't know yet.

212
00:09:21,227 --> 00:09:22,495
When does it?
Do we have the schedule?

213
00:09:22,562 --> 00:09:25,398
-It's scheduled for April.
-April.

214
00:09:25,464 --> 00:09:26,999
It'll be on Saturdays and Sundays
at 10:30 p.m.

215
00:09:27,066 --> 00:09:28,401
-Saturdays and Sundays.
-Yes.

216
00:09:28,467 --> 00:09:30,503
-Right after <i>Chef & My Fridge</i>.
-Right after this.

217
00:09:30,570 --> 00:09:32,471
-Really?
-Yes.

218
00:09:32,538 --> 00:09:37,176
We're doing our best
to help you promote this.

219
00:09:37,243 --> 00:09:40,046
That's very wonderful.

220
00:09:40,112 --> 00:09:43,082
Suk-ku was funnier than I expected.

221
00:09:43,149 --> 00:09:45,384
-Yes, people will love the series.
-It's great.

222
00:09:45,451 --> 00:09:48,688
Bong-sik, what do you play in the drama?

223
00:09:48,754 --> 00:09:51,991
Well, I'm not in that drama.

224
00:09:52,058 --> 00:09:53,659
I see. Is that so?

225
00:09:53,726 --> 00:09:55,061
FLUSTERED

226
00:09:55,127 --> 00:09:56,629
So you weren't on the cast.

227
00:09:56,696 --> 00:09:59,732
-He wasn't.
-Most people come with the other cast.

228
00:09:59,799 --> 00:10:03,302
If you have anything to promote,
we'll give you a chance.

229
00:10:03,369 --> 00:10:04,604
What do you want to promote?

230
00:10:04,670 --> 00:10:07,740
All my works haven't been publicized yet.

231
00:10:07,807 --> 00:10:11,077
It can be your personal affairs too.

232
00:10:11,143 --> 00:10:12,778
-Like his birthday?
-Anything you want to share?

233
00:10:12,845 --> 00:10:14,213
DID HE REMEMBER SOMETHING?

234
00:10:14,280 --> 00:10:16,549
-Is there something? Did you remember?
-Do you have it?

235
00:10:16,616 --> 00:10:20,620
Most people think
I don't have an Insta account.

236
00:10:20,686 --> 00:10:23,322
-Your Instagram account?
-That's a good one.

237
00:10:23,389 --> 00:10:25,324
-His social media account.
-Yes.

238
00:10:25,391 --> 00:10:28,961
-His posts are funny.
-His posts?

239
00:10:29,028 --> 00:10:30,529
How many followers do you have?

240
00:10:30,596 --> 00:10:31,797
I have 80K now.

241
00:10:31,864 --> 00:10:33,799
We'll put your handle in the caption.

242
00:10:33,866 --> 00:10:35,635
-Yes.
-Let's reach 100K.

243
00:10:35,701 --> 00:10:37,503
I hope it reaches 100K after this.

244
00:10:37,570 --> 00:10:39,939
-It's going up as we speak.
-Yes.

245
00:10:40,006 --> 00:10:42,274
-It's now 120K.
-He's happy.

246
00:10:42,341 --> 00:10:43,776
Let's keep an eye on it.

247
00:10:43,843 --> 00:10:47,913
Let's see. Suk-ku has
something in common with Poong.

248
00:10:47,980 --> 00:10:49,281
What is it?

249
00:10:49,348 --> 00:10:52,051
-You both studied art.
-I see.

250
00:10:52,118 --> 00:10:53,853
-Studying art.
-What was your major?

251
00:10:53,919 --> 00:10:57,423
I majored in video arts and documentary.

252
00:10:57,490 --> 00:10:58,858
I see.

253
00:10:58,924 --> 00:11:00,760
-Isn't that amazing?
-It is.

254
00:11:00,826 --> 00:11:02,862
School of the Art Institute of Chicago
and Hongik University.

255
00:11:02,928 --> 00:11:05,331
Why don't we do
a one-minute caricature match?

256
00:11:05,398 --> 00:11:07,366
-Who are we going to draw?
-Who?

257
00:11:07,433 --> 00:11:09,502
The man who took a 15-hour flight.

258
00:11:10,403 --> 00:11:13,072
He needs to take something home.

259
00:11:13,139 --> 00:11:15,608
I may not be as good of an artist,

260
00:11:15,675 --> 00:11:18,210
but I think I have an advantage
with this angle.

261
00:11:19,545 --> 00:11:21,247
-The location?
-He looks great here.

262
00:11:21,313 --> 00:11:22,748
I see. Okay.

263
00:11:22,815 --> 00:11:27,653
School of the Art Institute of Chicago
versus Hongik University.

264
00:11:27,720 --> 00:11:30,089
Their model is Edward Lee.

265
00:11:30,156 --> 00:11:31,691
All right. Ready, begin.

266
00:11:31,757 --> 00:11:33,726
Here we go. They've started.

267
00:11:33,793 --> 00:11:35,995
Just point out his key features.

268
00:11:36,962 --> 00:11:40,499
Bong-sik is filming this.

269
00:11:41,000 --> 00:11:42,802
DEAD SERIOUS

270
00:11:42,868 --> 00:11:45,638
-Chicago versus Hongdae.
-Is that my nose?

271
00:11:45,705 --> 00:11:47,106
Does he not like it?

272
00:11:47,173 --> 00:11:50,076
The viewers will also make their judgment.

273
00:11:51,177 --> 00:11:53,279
He picks up different things.

274
00:11:53,345 --> 00:11:56,315
It's almost like a portrait.

275
00:11:56,382 --> 00:11:57,616
I knew it.

276
00:11:57,683 --> 00:12:00,286
-Let's look at the process.
-It looks like him.

277
00:12:00,352 --> 00:12:03,823
Poong makes a big touches,

278
00:12:03,889 --> 00:12:06,759
whereas Suk-ku adds detailed touches.

279
00:12:06,826 --> 00:12:08,094
His touches aren't too big.

280
00:12:08,160 --> 00:12:10,362
If I win, do I beat the School
of the Art Institute of Chicago?

281
00:12:10,429 --> 00:12:12,865
-Of course.
-The honor of my alma mater is at stake.

282
00:12:12,932 --> 00:12:14,633
-It's a fight over pride.
-Yes.

283
00:12:14,700 --> 00:12:16,769
Art Institute of Chicago
versus Hongik University.

284
00:12:16,836 --> 00:12:17,903
I'm done.

285
00:12:17,970 --> 00:12:20,740
Turn it over if you're done.

286
00:12:20,806 --> 00:12:22,041
POONG FINISHES FIRST

287
00:12:22,541 --> 00:12:26,445
I think Suk-ku is drawing his profile.

288
00:12:26,512 --> 00:12:27,847
THE TENSION IS HIGHER
THAN EXPECTED

289
00:12:27,913 --> 00:12:29,348
It's all about competing.

290
00:12:29,415 --> 00:12:31,117
HE LOOKS SO COOL

291
00:12:31,183 --> 00:12:33,519
-He looks like a guru.
-Turn it over.

292
00:12:33,586 --> 00:12:35,087
Is that a bodhidharma painting?

293
00:12:35,154 --> 00:12:37,790
-Turn it over.
-Wait.

294
00:12:37,857 --> 00:12:39,391
They're both done.

295
00:12:39,458 --> 00:12:43,329
A match between Disney's alumnus
and a former webtoon artist,

296
00:12:43,395 --> 00:12:45,998
between Mr. Gu and Mr. Poong.

297
00:12:46,065 --> 00:12:49,635
Edward will make the decision
as the model.

298
00:12:49,702 --> 00:12:51,303
Please show us.

299
00:12:51,370 --> 00:12:53,472
KIM POONG'S DRAWING

300
00:12:54,173 --> 00:12:55,407
It looks good.

301
00:12:56,175 --> 00:12:57,176
DEVASTATED

302
00:12:57,243 --> 00:12:58,244
He gained a few pounds.

303
00:13:00,179 --> 00:13:02,615
It's hard to say that's not him.

304
00:13:02,681 --> 00:13:04,049
-It looks like him.
-It does.

305
00:13:04,116 --> 00:13:05,518
What do you think? Tell us.

306
00:13:05,584 --> 00:13:08,354
Is my head that big?

307
00:13:09,421 --> 00:13:10,489
HURT

308
00:13:10,556 --> 00:13:12,458
Your shoulders go out like this much.

309
00:13:13,859 --> 00:13:16,762
Well, it's a little bigger than others.

310
00:13:17,329 --> 00:13:20,699
I wanted to express
Chef Edward's solitude.

311
00:13:20,766 --> 00:13:24,870
The solitude that comes
from his 15-hour flight.

312
00:13:24,937 --> 00:13:28,274
-Here's Suk-ku's drawing!
-I'm sorry.

313
00:13:28,340 --> 00:13:30,009
-Show us.
-What's that?

314
00:13:30,075 --> 00:13:31,443
AMAZED

315
00:13:31,510 --> 00:13:32,711
What's that?

316
00:13:32,778 --> 00:13:33,779
Nice.

317
00:13:34,947 --> 00:13:36,749
-I can see him.
-I can.

318
00:13:36,816 --> 00:13:39,652
-Right? That's his profile.
-Yes.

319
00:13:41,253 --> 00:13:43,756
Edward suddenly takes the drawing.
What is it?

320
00:13:43,823 --> 00:13:45,291
Is he signing it?

321
00:13:45,357 --> 00:13:47,560
-Look. Suffering.
-Suffering.

322
00:13:47,626 --> 00:13:48,828
It's titled <i>Suffering</i>.

323
00:13:48,894 --> 00:13:51,964
It was <i>Solitude</i>,
but it changed to <i>Suffering</i>.

324
00:13:52,631 --> 00:13:54,533
Now, Edward will make the choice.

325
00:13:54,600 --> 00:13:58,003
Will it be the Art Institute of Chicago
or Hongik University?

326
00:14:00,039 --> 00:14:01,974
Will it be Mr. Gu or Mr. Poong?

327
00:14:02,041 --> 00:14:03,342
-That's not me.
-He lost.

328
00:14:04,643 --> 00:14:05,644
-He lost.
-It's not him.

329
00:14:05,711 --> 00:14:08,147
Then, Chef Eddy chooses…

330
00:14:08,214 --> 00:14:09,281
Yes, this one.

331
00:14:09,348 --> 00:14:13,052
-Can you sign it, please?
-Please sign it.

332
00:14:13,118 --> 00:14:14,486
You need the artist's signature.

333
00:14:14,553 --> 00:14:16,422
I'll sign it too.

334
00:14:16,488 --> 00:14:18,724
-This is a keepsake.
-It is.

335
00:14:18,791 --> 00:14:20,626
May I add a few extra touches?

336
00:14:20,693 --> 00:14:22,728
-Extra touches.
-A little more.

337
00:14:22,795 --> 00:14:25,831
He might put it up at his restaurant.

338
00:14:26,465 --> 00:14:29,735
A ONE-AND-ONLY DRAWING
ALONG WITH SON SUK-KU'S SIGNATURE

339
00:14:29,802 --> 00:14:31,937
That includes his signature.

340
00:14:32,004 --> 00:14:34,974
I don't know what he'll do with that,

341
00:14:35,040 --> 00:14:36,976
but he takes it anyway.

342
00:14:37,042 --> 00:14:38,711
This isn't like me.

343
00:14:38,777 --> 00:14:40,579
It's not like him.

344
00:14:42,214 --> 00:14:45,784
It looks just like him.

345
00:14:45,851 --> 00:14:48,621
-It does look like him.
-Look at that.

346
00:14:48,687 --> 00:14:50,723
It's like a photo.

347
00:14:50,789 --> 00:14:52,858
-Thank you.
-Sure.

348
00:14:52,925 --> 00:14:55,995
-Who knows which people will like more?
-Of course.

349
00:14:56,061 --> 00:14:58,564
Before we present the fridge,

350
00:14:58,631 --> 00:15:04,203
let's find out Suk-ku's orders
and decide on the contenders.

351
00:15:04,270 --> 00:15:08,240
Let's find out Suk-ku's orders.
Show us what they are.

352
00:15:08,307 --> 00:15:12,378
The first order is,
"I revere polar opposites."

353
00:15:12,444 --> 00:15:14,546
That was another great line.

354
00:15:14,613 --> 00:15:16,515
-It's from <i>My Liberation Notes</i>.
-<i>My Liberation Notes</i>.

355
00:15:17,283 --> 00:15:18,517
Love isn't enough.

356
00:15:21,620 --> 00:15:22,621
Revere me.

357
00:15:26,292 --> 00:15:29,862
I'll say, "polar opposites,"
and can you say, "I revere you"?

358
00:15:29,929 --> 00:15:32,431
-Why would you do that?
-Think of me as Ji-won.

359
00:15:32,498 --> 00:15:33,632
Polar opposites.

360
00:15:33,699 --> 00:15:36,068
I revere you.

361
00:15:37,136 --> 00:15:38,370
"I revere you."

362
00:15:38,437 --> 00:15:40,105
Look how pleased everyone is.

363
00:15:40,172 --> 00:15:42,708
-You're good.
-"You're good."

364
00:15:42,775 --> 00:15:45,411
-You have to do it quickly as you're told.
-Exactly.

365
00:15:45,477 --> 00:15:47,079
What kind of dishes are you looking for?

366
00:15:47,146 --> 00:15:48,247
For example,

367
00:15:48,314 --> 00:15:50,249
it's like serving cold naengmyeon

368
00:15:50,316 --> 00:15:53,218
served with steaming hot dumplings.

369
00:15:53,285 --> 00:15:55,888
Or a mix of soft texture

370
00:15:55,955 --> 00:15:57,222
mixed with crunchy texture.

371
00:15:57,289 --> 00:16:02,428
-I see.
-I once saw fried ice cream here.

372
00:16:02,494 --> 00:16:05,164
-Chef Eun-yeong did that recently.
-It was me.

373
00:16:05,230 --> 00:16:06,231
<i>I made ice cream </i>basi<i>.</i>

374
00:16:06,298 --> 00:16:08,267
-It was amazing to see her fry it.
-The <i>basi</i>.

375
00:16:08,334 --> 00:16:10,936
-I mean, ice cream is cold.
-Yes.

376
00:16:11,003 --> 00:16:13,272
-The ice cream <i>basi</i>.
-I wanted to try that.

377
00:16:13,339 --> 00:16:16,709
If you had come, I would've been revered.

378
00:16:16,775 --> 00:16:18,177
Then you would've made it here.

379
00:16:18,243 --> 00:16:20,446
I was very curious of such things.

380
00:16:20,512 --> 00:16:22,648
I think I like dishes that are

381
00:16:22,715 --> 00:16:25,985
a mix of different textures
or temperatures.

382
00:16:26,051 --> 00:16:27,886
Something interesting for your mouth.

383
00:16:27,953 --> 00:16:30,522
The second one is, "Be perilla leaves."

384
00:16:30,589 --> 00:16:31,657
-Be perilla leaves?
-Yes.

385
00:16:31,724 --> 00:16:34,994
-That's a wordplay on <i>Be Melodramatic</i>.
-Right.

386
00:16:35,060 --> 00:16:36,795
-<i>Be Melodramatic</i>.
-<i>Be Melodramatic </i>to be perilla leaves.

387
00:16:36,862 --> 00:16:39,331
I'm the type of person

388
00:16:39,398 --> 00:16:44,169
who thinks perilla leaves can be
a big thing globally.

389
00:16:44,903 --> 00:16:47,206
When I lived abroad as a teenager,

390
00:16:47,272 --> 00:16:50,342
I'd always pick up perilla leaves
at the Korean market

391
00:16:50,409 --> 00:16:52,778
and make omelet with those.

392
00:16:52,845 --> 00:16:54,246
-Omelet with perilla leaves?
-Yes.

393
00:16:54,313 --> 00:16:59,752
I particularly seem to like dishes
with a strong smell of perilla leaves.

394
00:17:00,486 --> 00:17:01,487
Do you like cilantro?

395
00:17:01,553 --> 00:17:04,289
I do. I love Southeast Asian cuisine.

396
00:17:04,356 --> 00:17:05,557
-I see.
-Okay.

397
00:17:05,624 --> 00:17:07,059
Do you have any in your fridge?

398
00:17:07,126 --> 00:17:08,227
I don't.

399
00:17:08,293 --> 00:17:11,363
-Actually, I…
-How are we going to make that?

400
00:17:11,430 --> 00:17:13,632
I want to apologize in advance.

401
00:17:13,699 --> 00:17:16,702
I really don't have
too many ingredients in my fridge.

402
00:17:16,769 --> 00:17:19,405
-We'll find out when we see it.
-Okay.

403
00:17:19,471 --> 00:17:21,407
I guess you don't cook a lot at home.

404
00:17:21,473 --> 00:17:24,943
Up until about seven to eight years ago,

405
00:17:25,010 --> 00:17:26,678
I used to cook often.

406
00:17:26,745 --> 00:17:29,314
But you can get just about anything
delivered now, so not anymore.

407
00:17:29,381 --> 00:17:31,183
-You're right.
-All right, then.

408
00:17:31,250 --> 00:17:33,852
First, the man
who flew 15 hours to get here.

409
00:17:33,919 --> 00:17:35,821
I'll give Chef Edward the first choice.

410
00:17:35,888 --> 00:17:39,691
I also love perilla leaves.

411
00:17:39,758 --> 00:17:41,260
-You do?
-I see.

412
00:17:41,326 --> 00:17:42,694
-Perilla leaves.
-Let's do it.

413
00:17:42,761 --> 00:17:44,296
Be perilla leaves.

414
00:17:44,363 --> 00:17:46,765
All right. Edward Lee takes his spot.

415
00:17:46,832 --> 00:17:50,235
You can either decide to fight Chef Edward
or pick one by the order.

416
00:17:50,302 --> 00:17:52,905
Hey, Sung-jun.
Chef Sung-jun raises his hand.

417
00:17:52,971 --> 00:17:57,076
This must be the match the whole country
has been waiting for.

418
00:17:57,142 --> 00:17:58,410
Whoa, are you doing it?

419
00:17:58,477 --> 00:18:00,512
-I'll do it.
-All right!

420
00:18:00,579 --> 00:18:02,915
<i>-It's been a year.</i>
<i>-Yes.</i>

421
00:18:02,981 --> 00:18:08,087
<i>Chef Edward and I had a fierce battle</i>
<i>in the final round a year ago.</i>

422
00:18:08,153 --> 00:18:11,056
I'll enter the return match after a year.

423
00:18:11,123 --> 00:18:13,125
This is huge.

424
00:18:13,192 --> 00:18:15,327
-It'd be a loss to lose.
-Yes, and if you win, it's the same.

425
00:18:15,394 --> 00:18:18,297
I'm a born Black Spoon,
so I must take challenges at all times.

426
00:18:18,363 --> 00:18:20,432
Gosh, challenges are his life.

427
00:18:21,100 --> 00:18:24,002
If he wins against him again,

428
00:18:24,069 --> 00:18:26,205
it'll be a huge blow to him.

429
00:18:26,271 --> 00:18:28,006
Yes, that's a lot of pressure.

430
00:18:28,073 --> 00:18:30,275
-My gosh.
-Chef Edward, yes.

431
00:18:30,342 --> 00:18:33,378
-He may fly back for 15 hours in tears.
-Yes.

432
00:18:33,445 --> 00:18:36,682
-He had to do this.
-This is cruel.

433
00:18:36,748 --> 00:18:39,418
Now, what about,
"I revere polar opposites"?

434
00:18:39,485 --> 00:18:40,953
Is anyone up for it?

435
00:18:41,019 --> 00:18:43,388
-Chef Ho-young.
-Chef Ho-young, do you want to do it?

436
00:18:43,455 --> 00:18:46,125
If Chef Eun-yeong says she'll do it,
then I'll do it too.

437
00:18:46,191 --> 00:18:47,459
-I see.
-Why?

438
00:18:47,526 --> 00:18:49,695
We both don't have a loss yet.

439
00:18:49,761 --> 00:18:51,029
-He's right.
-Is that so?

440
00:18:51,096 --> 00:18:52,831
I wanted to take her down
with this chance.

441
00:18:52,898 --> 00:18:54,633
-I see.
-To take her down.

442
00:18:54,700 --> 00:18:56,568
He wants to give her
that bitter taste of loss.

443
00:18:56,635 --> 00:18:59,872
-Then I must accept his challenge.
-Okay.

444
00:18:59,938 --> 00:19:02,674
The contenders were decided
for "I revere polar opposites."

445
00:19:02,741 --> 00:19:05,777
Chef Ho-young and Eun-yeong are
up against each other.

446
00:19:05,844 --> 00:19:10,582
Let's find out
what Suk-ku has in his fridge.

447
00:19:10,649 --> 00:19:11,950
Do you live alone?

448
00:19:12,017 --> 00:19:13,652
-I live with my younger brother.
-Younger brother.

449
00:19:13,719 --> 00:19:15,687
-And you share that with him?
-He should have some food.

450
00:19:15,754 --> 00:19:17,289
-I see.
-Your actual brother?

451
00:19:17,356 --> 00:19:19,892
My brother and I have been
living together for over a decade.

452
00:19:19,958 --> 00:19:21,160
-I see.
-He has a brother.

453
00:19:21,226 --> 00:19:22,828
Let's take a look.

454
00:19:22,895 --> 00:19:25,197
-I should write it down. I'm nervous.
-Suk-ku's fridge.

455
00:19:25,264 --> 00:19:28,200
We present Suk-ku's fridge.

456
00:19:28,267 --> 00:19:30,636
-All right. Okay.
-I see.

457
00:19:30,702 --> 00:19:31,703
He has a lot of stuff.

458
00:19:31,770 --> 00:19:34,373
-All right. Okay.
-I see.

459
00:19:34,439 --> 00:19:35,440
He has a lot of stuff.

460
00:19:35,507 --> 00:19:37,509
There are lots of things. It looks full.

461
00:19:37,576 --> 00:19:41,346
-I thought it'd be empty. This isn't bad.
-I'm glad.

462
00:19:41,413 --> 00:19:43,182
This is good. You have some stuff.

463
00:19:43,248 --> 00:19:44,583
-Okay.
-Do I?

464
00:19:44,650 --> 00:19:46,218
-Yes.
-These are more than enough.

465
00:19:46,285 --> 00:19:49,488
It does seem odd
to see your fridge here, right?

466
00:19:49,555 --> 00:19:50,789
Yes, it does.

467
00:19:50,856 --> 00:19:52,324
I feel like

468
00:19:52,391 --> 00:19:54,359
-I'm standing there naked.
-I see.

469
00:19:55,093 --> 00:19:56,962
First of all,

470
00:19:57,029 --> 00:19:59,665
I see some chicken breast.

471
00:19:59,731 --> 00:20:03,635
My brother works out,
and he's a pretty big guy.

472
00:20:03,702 --> 00:20:05,804
So he eats that for protein.

473
00:20:05,871 --> 00:20:07,573
Don't you also eat it to stay in shape?

474
00:20:07,639 --> 00:20:08,640
I rarely eat that.

475
00:20:08,707 --> 00:20:10,309
I'm bad at staying on a diet.

476
00:20:10,375 --> 00:20:12,377
But in <i>The Roundup</i>,

477
00:20:12,444 --> 00:20:15,047
-you were in a great shape.
-You looked great.

478
00:20:15,113 --> 00:20:17,449
I don't get
how you aren't on a strict diet.

479
00:20:17,516 --> 00:20:20,485
I used to stay
on a strict diet until 9 p.m.,

480
00:20:20,552 --> 00:20:22,221
but in the end,

481
00:20:22,287 --> 00:20:24,756
I found myself eating
in the middle of the night.

482
00:20:24,823 --> 00:20:27,759
It was better for me to eat
what I wanted and when I wanted it.

483
00:20:27,826 --> 00:20:30,529
So you'll eat what you want to eat,
then work out more.

484
00:20:30,596 --> 00:20:32,431
-Yes.
-That's the idea.

485
00:20:32,497 --> 00:20:35,467
Look how he takes care of himself.

486
00:20:35,534 --> 00:20:37,569
These must be for your swollen eyes.

487
00:20:37,636 --> 00:20:39,905
These are for swollen eyes.

488
00:20:39,972 --> 00:20:43,208
Great analysis.
His eyelids were important.

489
00:20:43,275 --> 00:20:44,876
-Of course.
-Yes, his eyelids.

490
00:20:44,943 --> 00:20:47,579
That's how he can play
a villain and a good guy.

491
00:20:47,646 --> 00:20:51,049
What are these? These are in yellow boxes.

492
00:20:51,116 --> 00:20:52,517
Those aren't food.

493
00:20:52,584 --> 00:20:55,921
-Lemon juice. Technically, you can eat it.
-Lemon juice.

494
00:20:55,988 --> 00:20:58,457
A lot of people
seem to take this recently.

495
00:20:58,523 --> 00:21:02,694
I heard it was in trend
on the social media,

496
00:21:02,761 --> 00:21:04,329
so I bought some.

497
00:21:04,930 --> 00:21:06,632
-So, you bought these?
-You bought those.

498
00:21:06,698 --> 00:21:09,701
Do you tend to pay attention
to what's in trend?

499
00:21:09,768 --> 00:21:12,070
Yes, I often buy and take

500
00:21:12,137 --> 00:21:13,905
trending health supplements.

501
00:21:13,972 --> 00:21:17,409
He stays sharply in trend
when it comes to health.

502
00:21:17,476 --> 00:21:19,578
He's a guy who follows the trend.

503
00:21:19,645 --> 00:21:22,514
And the second shelf has rice.

504
00:21:22,581 --> 00:21:25,050
-He has lots of rice.
-He does.

505
00:21:25,117 --> 00:21:26,818
It means you often eat at home.

506
00:21:26,885 --> 00:21:29,354
What do you usually cook at home?

507
00:21:29,421 --> 00:21:31,423
I'd make curry and…

508
00:21:31,490 --> 00:21:35,794
The thing is, I always throw in tomatoes
to everything I make.

509
00:21:35,861 --> 00:21:37,729
-Tomatoes.
-Really?

510
00:21:37,796 --> 00:21:38,830
That's a great tip.

511
00:21:38,897 --> 00:21:42,067
I even put tomato into kimchi jjigae.

512
00:21:42,134 --> 00:21:44,903
-It'll taste good.
-It will. It's great with kimchi jjigae.

513
00:21:44,970 --> 00:21:47,539
-It's good with kimchi.
-It makes it more savory.

514
00:21:47,606 --> 00:21:49,041
-It was good.
-It is.

515
00:21:49,107 --> 00:21:50,309
Does he have tomatoes?

516
00:21:50,375 --> 00:21:51,877
-He does.
-He has tomatoes.

517
00:21:51,943 --> 00:21:54,913
-And tomato juice too.
-He has the juice pack too.

518
00:21:54,980 --> 00:21:57,516
-That's 100% tomato.
-Yes.

519
00:21:57,582 --> 00:22:00,085
-You said you get food delivered now.
-Yes.

520
00:22:00,152 --> 00:22:02,754
Can you tell us what you usually order?

521
00:22:02,821 --> 00:22:05,157
For dessert, I order

522
00:22:05,223 --> 00:22:08,994
bubble tea and frozen yogurt.

523
00:22:09,061 --> 00:22:11,029
Bubble tea and frozen yogurt.

524
00:22:11,096 --> 00:22:12,097
Sweet things.

525
00:22:12,164 --> 00:22:15,000
-He's eating all kinds of Gen Z items.
-He is. You get those delivered.

526
00:22:15,067 --> 00:22:17,936
That frozen yogurt place was
a brand new world to me.

527
00:22:18,003 --> 00:22:19,638
Do you throw in toppings?

528
00:22:19,705 --> 00:22:21,139
I always order the same thing.

529
00:22:21,206 --> 00:22:22,607
-I'd get the chocolate shell,
-Yes.

530
00:22:22,674 --> 00:22:27,479
-honeycomb,
-The honey.

531
00:22:27,546 --> 00:22:30,382
and one type of fruit I want that day.

532
00:22:30,449 --> 00:22:34,386
-That's very popular now.
-He really is following the Gen Z trend.

533
00:22:34,453 --> 00:22:36,054
-It's so good.
-It is.

534
00:22:36,121 --> 00:22:38,757
-I found kimchi. Did someone make these?
-Kimchi.

535
00:22:38,824 --> 00:22:41,827
-It was probably my mother.
-Your mother.

536
00:22:41,893 --> 00:22:42,894
It looks good.

537
00:22:42,961 --> 00:22:45,931
What's your favorite dish
among your mom's food?

538
00:22:45,997 --> 00:22:48,900
I eat most things deliciously, actually.

539
00:22:49,601 --> 00:22:53,038
People say
some food smells too fishy, right?

540
00:22:53,105 --> 00:22:54,639
-Yes, and the fat smell.
-Yes.

541
00:22:54,706 --> 00:22:56,675
By the time I feel it's too fishy,

542
00:22:56,742 --> 00:22:58,643
it's probably too fishy for anyone to eat.

543
00:22:58,710 --> 00:23:01,713
-I never catch on to such things.
-You don't.

544
00:23:01,780 --> 00:23:04,616
I find even spicy food mostly delicious.

545
00:23:04,683 --> 00:23:06,451
-I see.
-Yes.

546
00:23:06,518 --> 00:23:09,254
And finally, I see perilla leaves.

547
00:23:09,321 --> 00:23:11,490
-Whoa.
-Be perilla leaves.

548
00:23:11,556 --> 00:23:14,993
Do you want it to smell subtle
or give off a strong smell of the leaves?

549
00:23:15,627 --> 00:23:18,130
It could even be the center of the dish.

550
00:23:18,196 --> 00:23:20,298
They can even have it
as the star of the dish.

551
00:23:20,365 --> 00:23:21,767
-I see.
-Perilla leaves as the star?

552
00:23:21,833 --> 00:23:22,868
-That's not easy.
-It won't be easy.

553
00:23:22,934 --> 00:23:25,003
And now, the freezer.

554
00:23:25,070 --> 00:23:27,839
I see. You must like meat.

555
00:23:27,906 --> 00:23:30,776
These are all Korean beef,
strip loin steak and tenderloin.

556
00:23:30,842 --> 00:23:32,811
-And even shin foreshank.
-And shin foreshank.

557
00:23:32,878 --> 00:23:34,646
Do you care about the cuts?

558
00:23:34,713 --> 00:23:36,648
You know what?

559
00:23:36,715 --> 00:23:40,719
I couldn't even tell the difference
between pork and beef.

560
00:23:40,786 --> 00:23:41,787
What?

561
00:23:41,853 --> 00:23:45,090
-Who knows what's sirloin or tenderloin?
-Most are like him.

562
00:23:45,157 --> 00:23:47,159
But we can tell between pork and beef.

563
00:23:47,225 --> 00:23:48,226
I know it now.

564
00:23:48,293 --> 00:23:49,694
How long did it take you?

565
00:23:49,761 --> 00:23:52,130
-I found out through team dinners.
-I see.

566
00:23:52,197 --> 00:23:54,266
-Some people can tell raw fish apart, too.
-Yes.

567
00:23:54,332 --> 00:23:58,336
The only two kinds I can tell are
yellowtail and salmon.

568
00:23:58,403 --> 00:23:59,838
And tuna, too.

569
00:23:59,905 --> 00:24:03,508
-You can tell those apart by their color!
-The colors are different.

570
00:24:03,575 --> 00:24:05,844
-I can't tell other than those three.
-I get it.

571
00:24:05,911 --> 00:24:06,945
You aren't a gourmet.

572
00:24:07,012 --> 00:24:08,547
-Not at all.
-I see.

573
00:24:08,613 --> 00:24:12,350
He's the easiest type to cook for.

574
00:24:12,417 --> 00:24:13,885
-I love it.
-His appetite is ordinary.

575
00:24:13,952 --> 00:24:16,421
He wouldn't notice if you served pork
saying it was beef.

576
00:24:16,488 --> 00:24:18,790
YOU CAN DECEIVE HIM
STRAIGHT TO HIS FACE

577
00:24:18,857 --> 00:24:21,326
Hey, Suk-ku is here.
You don't have to use beef.

578
00:24:22,194 --> 00:24:24,362
HE KNOWS NOW

579
00:24:24,429 --> 00:24:26,898
And what's next? Look at these.

580
00:24:26,965 --> 00:24:31,069
I found some seafood.
Cuttlefish. It's cuttlefish, right?

581
00:24:31,136 --> 00:24:32,938
-Abalone.
-What is it?

582
00:24:33,004 --> 00:24:34,306
-I see.
-Abalone.

583
00:24:34,372 --> 00:24:37,509
-Do you like abalone?
-I do.

584
00:24:37,576 --> 00:24:39,978
-I'm seeing some balls. Meatballs?
-Meatballs.

585
00:24:40,045 --> 00:24:43,181
That was all for Suk-ku's fridge.

586
00:24:43,248 --> 00:24:44,850
He had more food than I thought.

587
00:24:44,916 --> 00:24:46,485
-Right?
-Was that okay?

588
00:24:46,551 --> 00:24:48,954
-That was quite a lot.
-It was a lot.

589
00:24:49,020 --> 00:24:51,223
-It wasn't so bad.
-No, it wasn't.

590
00:24:51,289 --> 00:24:52,691
<i>I have an announcement.</i>

591
00:24:52,757 --> 00:24:57,496
<i>Until now, only the new chefs</i>
<i>got to use the perks.</i>

592
00:24:57,562 --> 00:25:01,099
-And now, everyone can use it.
-I see.

593
00:25:01,166 --> 00:25:06,404
However,
only one person per team gets to use it.

594
00:25:06,471 --> 00:25:08,640
<i>If one of you uses it first,</i>

595
00:25:08,707 --> 00:25:11,209
<i>the next chefs can't.</i>

596
00:25:11,276 --> 00:25:12,377
<i>We should hold a meeting.</i>

597
00:25:12,444 --> 00:25:14,479
-You have another perk.
-What is it?

598
00:25:14,546 --> 00:25:18,783
The One-minute UNICHEF
benefit is available.

599
00:25:18,850 --> 00:25:20,519
<i>Like the meringue incident.</i>

600
00:25:20,585 --> 00:25:21,586
<i>One-minute UNICHEF.</i>

601
00:25:21,653 --> 00:25:23,622
<i>We can ask them to help for a minute?</i>

602
00:25:23,688 --> 00:25:24,856
They should design a good plan.

603
00:25:24,923 --> 00:25:26,358
HOW WILL THE NEW PERK
IMPACT THE MATCH?

604
00:25:26,424 --> 00:25:30,795
<i>The first round</i>
<i>with ingredients from Suk-ku's fridge.</i>

605
00:25:30,862 --> 00:25:33,832
They both currently hold two stars.

606
00:25:33,899 --> 00:25:36,334
They both haven't lost yet.

607
00:25:36,401 --> 00:25:38,970
A match between the top dogs
of this season.

608
00:25:39,037 --> 00:25:42,607
Before Chef Eun-yeong appeared
on <i>Culinary Class Wars</i>,

609
00:25:42,674 --> 00:25:44,809
I evaluated her once before.

610
00:25:44,876 --> 00:25:48,113
-You were Chef Eun-yeong's judge.
-Is that so?

611
00:25:48,179 --> 00:25:50,615
And as she rose to her status,

612
00:25:50,682 --> 00:25:53,084
she has become almost too bold.

613
00:25:53,151 --> 00:25:56,521
-I'll turn her back into a coward.
-I see!

614
00:25:56,588 --> 00:25:58,156
That's the scariest thing to say.

615
00:25:58,223 --> 00:25:59,724
"I'll make you a coward again."

616
00:25:59,791 --> 00:26:01,693
"I'll make you a coward."

617
00:26:01,760 --> 00:26:06,131
We all wonder if you'll use a perk
starting with the first round.

618
00:26:06,197 --> 00:26:08,466
If any of you uses the perk,

619
00:26:08,533 --> 00:26:11,303
your next teammate
won't be able to use it.

620
00:26:11,369 --> 00:26:14,773
I'll use it.

621
00:26:14,839 --> 00:26:17,943
I must win this round,
so I will use a perk.

622
00:26:18,710 --> 00:26:20,345
Chef Eddy, would that be okay?

623
00:26:20,412 --> 00:26:22,914
-She'll use the perk?
-She will.

624
00:26:22,981 --> 00:26:27,419
-She stole it from me.
-She did. She stole it from you.

625
00:26:27,485 --> 00:26:28,887
You should talk to him first.

626
00:26:28,954 --> 00:26:30,422
Is that okay, Chef Eddy?

627
00:26:30,488 --> 00:26:32,190
-It's fine.
-It's fine.

628
00:26:32,257 --> 00:26:34,025
Ho-young should use it too.

629
00:26:34,092 --> 00:26:36,027
But you're a returning chef.
Will you use it?

630
00:26:36,695 --> 00:26:38,296
Returning chef or whatever,

631
00:26:38,363 --> 00:26:41,466
-I have to win too, so I will.
-My gosh.

632
00:26:41,533 --> 00:26:44,936
Have you asked Chef Sung-jun?
Are you not going to use it?

633
00:26:45,003 --> 00:26:47,939
Edward isn't using it,
so I'm fine with that.

634
00:26:48,006 --> 00:26:50,408
THE CLASS OF THE 1ST AND 2ND PLACES
OF CULINARY CLASS WARS

635
00:26:50,475 --> 00:26:52,877
In that case, which one will you use?

636
00:26:52,944 --> 00:26:54,446
-Which one will it be?
-This is important.

637
00:26:54,512 --> 00:26:57,482
I'll use the UNICHEF.

638
00:26:57,549 --> 00:26:59,718
-UNICHEF.
-It's okay. UNICHEF is fine.

639
00:26:59,784 --> 00:27:01,186
I'll keep my eyes on the time

640
00:27:01,252 --> 00:27:03,722
and pick the most adequate chef
for the task.

641
00:27:03,788 --> 00:27:04,923
-"The most adequate chef."
-Yes.

642
00:27:04,990 --> 00:27:06,124
And Chef Ho-young?

643
00:27:06,191 --> 00:27:08,760
I'll start a minute earlier.

644
00:27:08,827 --> 00:27:11,696
STARTING 1 MINUTE EARLY

645
00:27:12,263 --> 00:27:14,199
-You'll begin a minute earlier?
-Come on.

646
00:27:14,265 --> 00:27:16,568
-Are you scared? Are you scared?
-You're a returning chef.

647
00:27:16,635 --> 00:27:18,269
-Are you scared?
-I'm a bit scared.

648
00:27:18,336 --> 00:27:19,838
-A bit?
-No, you have to win this.

649
00:27:19,904 --> 00:27:22,007
We have to use it.

650
00:27:22,073 --> 00:27:25,010
I need as much time as I can
to make today's dish.

651
00:27:25,076 --> 00:27:28,713
That's why I want to begin first
and make it look more complete.

652
00:27:28,780 --> 00:27:31,683
The returning chef says
he'll use 16 minutes.

653
00:27:31,750 --> 00:27:34,019
I love the sound of 16 minutes.

654
00:27:35,387 --> 00:27:37,455
CHEF EUN-YEONG'S INGREDIENTS: LEMON
JUICE CHICKEN BREAST, PEANUT BUTTER

655
00:27:37,522 --> 00:27:39,557
CREAM CHEESE, TOMATO JUICE,
SEASONED LAVER, GEOTJEORI, NOODLES

656
00:27:39,624 --> 00:27:41,292
Chef Eun-yeong, what's your dish?

657
00:27:41,359 --> 00:27:44,329
My dish is called Reverent Chicken.

658
00:27:44,396 --> 00:27:46,131
-Reverent Chicken.
-Yes.

659
00:27:46,197 --> 00:27:47,666
-I see.
-Reverent Chicken.

660
00:27:47,732 --> 00:27:49,267
-Is it a chicken dish?
-Yes, a chicken dish.

661
00:27:49,334 --> 00:27:52,971
There's a famous cold chicken dish
in Chinese cuisine called bon bon chicken.

662
00:27:53,038 --> 00:27:56,841
I'll make bon bon chicken
and fry some noodles in a dish shape

663
00:27:56,908 --> 00:27:58,910
for him to enjoy together.

664
00:27:58,977 --> 00:28:02,781
Bon bon chicken tastes chewy and cold,

665
00:28:02,847 --> 00:28:05,316
while the fried noodles will taste
crunchy and warm.

666
00:28:05,383 --> 00:28:09,120
I'll use the opposite textures
and temperatures

667
00:28:09,187 --> 00:28:12,257
to prepare a chicken dish he will revere.

668
00:28:13,091 --> 00:28:15,160
CHEF HO-YOUNG'S INGREDIENTS:
STEVIA CHERRY TOMATOES, TUNA SAUCE

669
00:28:15,226 --> 00:28:17,262
HALF-DRIED CUTTLEFISH, CODFISH
FILLETS, LEMON JUICE, ABALONE

670
00:28:17,328 --> 00:28:19,864
Up against her is Chef Ho-young.
What did you prepare?

671
00:28:19,931 --> 00:28:21,633
I'm going to make…

672
00:28:22,200 --> 00:28:24,636
<i>Su-Su-Su-Super Udon</i>

673
00:28:24,703 --> 00:28:26,838
<i>Su-Su-Su-Super Udon</i>

674
00:28:27,405 --> 00:28:28,907
THE DANCING FAIRY RETURNS

675
00:28:28,973 --> 00:28:30,608
-What?
-Where have I seen that?

676
00:28:30,675 --> 00:28:33,044
-It's aespa.
-Yes, aespa.

677
00:28:33,111 --> 00:28:35,046
-"Supernova"?
-It was "Supernova."

678
00:28:35,113 --> 00:28:37,048
THE DANCING FAIRY VER.

679
00:28:37,115 --> 00:28:38,917
I'M GETTING ADDICTED

680
00:28:38,983 --> 00:28:40,752
<i>Su-Su-Su-Super Udon</i>

681
00:28:40,819 --> 00:28:41,820
STARING

682
00:28:41,886 --> 00:28:45,090
I was too invested in his dance
that I didn't get what he said.

683
00:28:45,156 --> 00:28:47,292
-Me too.
-What's it called?

684
00:28:47,358 --> 00:28:49,461
-Su-Su-Su-Super Udon.
-Su-Su-Su-Super Udon.

685
00:28:49,527 --> 00:28:52,497
-Super Udon.
-Super Udon.

686
00:28:52,564 --> 00:28:53,998
CHEF JUNG HO-YOUNG'S
SU-SU-SU-SUPER UDON

687
00:28:54,065 --> 00:28:56,401
His dance lingers with me for too long.

688
00:28:57,368 --> 00:28:58,737
<i>Su-Su-Su-Super Udon</i>

689
00:28:58,803 --> 00:29:00,105
That's his best move.

690
00:29:00,171 --> 00:29:03,174
Yes, so by super, does it mean
you'll make the noodles here?

691
00:29:03,241 --> 00:29:05,643
I'm going to make the noodles right here.

692
00:29:05,710 --> 00:29:08,480
Then, I'll make the soup base with tomato

693
00:29:08,546 --> 00:29:11,216
and finish cold and chewy udon.

694
00:29:11,282 --> 00:29:15,320
I saw abalone, codfish fillets,
and cuttlefish too.

695
00:29:15,386 --> 00:29:17,555
I'll serve the udon with some fritters,

696
00:29:17,622 --> 00:29:19,924
so he can take a bite of the hot fry

697
00:29:19,991 --> 00:29:22,227
and even dip it in the cold broth.

698
00:29:22,293 --> 00:29:25,797
You'll taste sweetness and saltiness
in the hot and cold dishes.

699
00:29:25,864 --> 00:29:28,700
I'll make two polar opposites.

700
00:29:29,367 --> 00:29:30,435
That's tough to beat.

701
00:29:30,502 --> 00:29:34,072
When you just hear about these,
which do you prefer more?

702
00:29:34,139 --> 00:29:37,375
If I may be blunt, well…

703
00:29:37,942 --> 00:29:39,344
Hmm…

704
00:29:39,410 --> 00:29:42,347
-Chef Ho-young's dishes.
-Gosh.

705
00:29:42,981 --> 00:29:44,916
-His…
-Su-Su-Su-Super Udon.

706
00:29:44,983 --> 00:29:47,152
I was too shocked to continue speaking.

707
00:29:47,218 --> 00:29:50,455
-Su-Su-Su-Super Udon.
-His image lingers.

708
00:29:50,522 --> 00:29:51,990
It's not just him.

709
00:29:52,056 --> 00:29:54,759
Su-Su-Su-Super Udon seemed to use

710
00:29:56,795 --> 00:29:58,763
more of the ingredients

711
00:29:58,830 --> 00:30:00,999
that I like to eat.

712
00:30:01,065 --> 00:30:03,234
-I see.
-That'd be the case.

713
00:30:03,301 --> 00:30:05,036
He gets a head start.

714
00:30:05,103 --> 00:30:08,673
But if both dishes are delicious,

715
00:30:08,740 --> 00:30:14,312
I'll go back to how moved I was
to see Chef Edward on the show,

716
00:30:14,379 --> 00:30:18,750
challenging himself
to show his creativity.

717
00:30:18,817 --> 00:30:22,287
I'd be quite moved
if I saw something like that.

718
00:30:22,353 --> 00:30:25,123
