Chef Edward cooks steak.

1668
01:10:03,232 --> 01:10:06,335
First, he put the kimchi out
like a side dish.

1669
01:10:07,002 --> 01:10:08,270
ADDING BUTTER

1670
01:10:08,337 --> 01:10:09,538
ADDING PERILLA LEAF

1671
01:10:09,605 --> 01:10:11,140
He put perilla leaf in the pan.

1672
01:10:12,341 --> 01:10:17,179
SHOWERING WITH BUTTER
AND THE SCENT OF PERILLA LEAF

1673
01:10:17,246 --> 01:10:18,314
-And now, five minutes!
-Yes.

1674
01:10:18,380 --> 01:10:20,416
-Please go out to the field, Jung-hwan.
-Yes.

1675
01:10:20,482 --> 01:10:23,118
It's an honor to taste something
in a battle like this one.

1676
01:10:23,185 --> 01:10:27,223
-I'll remain cool and help you.
-There are lots of things to check.

1677
01:10:27,289 --> 01:10:29,358
What's he doing over there?

1678
01:10:29,425 --> 01:10:33,295
-It looks hot.
-He's using gnocchi water in that pan.

1679
01:10:33,362 --> 01:10:36,599
He added gnocchi water to butter

1680
01:10:36,665 --> 01:10:39,235
to emulsify the sauce
and coat the gnocchi.

1681
01:10:39,301 --> 01:10:41,837
He's coating the gnocchi?

1682
01:10:41,904 --> 01:10:46,008
Chef Edward is already putting
the noodles on the plate.

1683
01:10:46,075 --> 01:10:47,743
It must be fully cooked.

1684
01:10:47,810 --> 01:10:50,045
-The steak is still on heat.
-Yes.

1685
01:10:50,112 --> 01:10:52,081
He put a lot of work into the ragu.

1686
01:10:52,147 --> 01:10:54,350
-The ragu! Try the ragu.
-The gnocchi is done too.

1687
01:10:54,416 --> 01:10:57,286
-The ragu?
-Yes, he put a lot of work into it.

1688
01:10:57,353 --> 01:10:58,687
-Yes, of course.
-Yes.

1689
01:10:58,754 --> 01:10:59,788
I'll try it.

1690
01:10:59,855 --> 01:11:02,625
-Jung-hwan, how's the ragu?
-Yes?

1691
01:11:02,691 --> 01:11:04,226
What's it like?

1692
01:11:04,293 --> 01:11:05,728
TELL ME

1693
01:11:05,794 --> 01:11:08,564
-Ragu! Tell us!
-His facial expression.

1694
01:11:08,631 --> 01:11:11,400
It doesn't taste like the ragu I know.

1695
01:11:12,001 --> 01:11:15,137
I think the curry added
a lot of Indian flavor into this.

1696
01:11:15,204 --> 01:11:18,474
As I mentioned, this is
the Art Institute of Chicago ragu.

1697
01:11:18,540 --> 01:11:19,775
-This is Chicago?
-Yes.

1698
01:11:19,842 --> 01:11:22,344
Is that served in the cafeteria?

1699
01:11:22,945 --> 01:11:24,113
-Served in the cafeteria?
-Indian?

1700
01:11:24,179 --> 01:11:26,615
It has a strong Indian flavor,

1701
01:11:26,682 --> 01:11:28,951
-and it also smells a bit sour.
-I see.

1702
01:11:29,018 --> 01:11:30,886
There's a bit of sourness.

1703
01:11:30,953 --> 01:11:32,788
-Did you do that on purpose?
-Yes.

1704
01:11:32,855 --> 01:11:34,957
He added the sourness on purpose.

1705
01:11:35,024 --> 01:11:37,192
EDWARD BEGINS
TO PRESENT HIS FOOD

1706
01:11:39,528 --> 01:11:41,463
CLASSY CERAMIC DISHES

1707
01:11:42,631 --> 01:11:46,235
-The cream sauce goes on the noodles!
-The sauce was for the noodles!

1708
01:11:46,302 --> 01:11:47,903
That looks so good.

1709
01:11:49,505 --> 01:11:52,141
-The kimchi.
-The stir-fried kimchi.

1710
01:11:52,207 --> 01:11:55,044
-It goes on the perilla leaf sauce.
-It was for the noodles.

1711
01:11:55,110 --> 01:11:58,147
I've never imagined
such a combination before.

1712
01:11:58,213 --> 01:11:59,214
He uses it as topping.

1713
01:11:59,281 --> 01:12:00,416
-Jung-hwan!
-Yes?

1714
01:12:00,482 --> 01:12:03,585
-Eddy's perilla leaf sauce.
-Perilla leaf sauce.

1715
01:12:03,652 --> 01:12:05,988
Some are left in the blender.

1716
01:12:06,055 --> 01:12:07,156
Yes.

1717
01:12:07,222 --> 01:12:08,524
Try some leftovers.

1718
01:12:09,358 --> 01:12:10,726
-Okay.
-Whoa, man.

1719
01:12:10,793 --> 01:12:12,995
-It smells mild.
-It does?

1720
01:12:13,062 --> 01:12:16,065
Now, the perilla leaf sauce!

1721
01:12:16,765 --> 01:12:17,933
What's it like?

1722
01:12:18,000 --> 01:12:19,601
PERILLA LEAF, SSAMJANG,
GREEN ONION,

1723
01:12:19,668 --> 01:12:21,470
CHILI PEPPER, GARLIC,
OLIVE OIL, MILK =?

1724
01:12:21,537 --> 01:12:23,405
-What's it like?
-Gosh, this is…

1725
01:12:23,472 --> 01:12:24,606
Is it good?

1726
01:12:24,673 --> 01:12:25,774
It's amazing.

1727
01:12:25,841 --> 01:12:28,644
Right? He put a lot of work into it.

1728
01:12:28,711 --> 01:12:30,346
It has deep flavors.

1729
01:12:33,415 --> 01:12:36,218
EDWARD ONLY HAS
TO FINISH THE MEAT

1730
01:12:36,285 --> 01:12:40,489
Chef Eddy begins to cut the steak,
and he tries a bite too.

1731
01:12:40,556 --> 01:12:42,624
-Excuse me.
-He feeds him one too!

1732
01:12:42,691 --> 01:12:44,760
-Excuse me.
-He feeds him one too!

1733
01:12:44,827 --> 01:12:46,895
He just fed him!

1734
01:12:48,664 --> 01:12:50,132
-How is it?
-It's good.

1735
01:12:50,199 --> 01:12:52,701
Is it good? He must've been confident
when he gave that to you.

1736
01:12:52,768 --> 01:12:55,504
It's cooked so evenly.
Gosh, that's amazing.

1737
01:12:55,571 --> 01:12:58,774
-He cooked that in this pan?
-The steak looks great.

1738
01:12:58,841 --> 01:13:00,342
KWON SUNG-JUN
IS FINISHING UP TOO!

1739
01:13:00,843 --> 01:13:04,012
HE CHOPS STEVIA CHERRY TOMATOES
INTO SMALL PIECES

1740
01:13:04,079 --> 01:13:05,681
JULIENNED PERILLA LEAVES,
CHOPPED TOMATO, ONION

1741
01:13:05,748 --> 01:13:07,983
-What did Chef Sung-jun just make?
-I'm making salsa.

1742
01:13:08,050 --> 01:13:09,051
Salsa.

1743
01:13:09,118 --> 01:13:11,253
He's seasoning salsa with salt.

1744
01:13:11,987 --> 01:13:13,589
BLACK PEPPER

1745
01:13:13,655 --> 01:13:15,924
TRUFFLE OIL

1746
01:13:15,991 --> 01:13:17,326
GENEROUS AMOUNT

1747
01:13:18,594 --> 01:13:21,964
SMELLS LIKE TRUFFLE OIL

1748
01:13:22,030 --> 01:13:24,133
Darn it. This is truffle oil.

1749
01:13:24,199 --> 01:13:28,036
He must've put in truffle oil,
thinking it was olive oil.

1750
01:13:28,103 --> 01:13:30,873
-He made a mistake.
-He just made a big mistake.

1751
01:13:30,939 --> 01:13:33,642
-It's okay.
-Are you sure it's okay?

1752
01:13:33,709 --> 01:13:36,311
-What if it's even better?
-Wait.

1753
01:13:36,378 --> 01:13:38,881
EDWARD GETS WATER IN A WINE GLASS

1754
01:13:40,149 --> 01:13:42,551
ARRANGING PERILLA LEAVES?

1755
01:13:43,051 --> 01:13:44,787
HE RUNS!

1756
01:13:44,853 --> 01:13:46,889
Wait, something must've gone wrong
for Chef Edward too!

1757
01:13:46,955 --> 01:13:48,157
-Why?
-Something is burning.

1758
01:13:48,223 --> 01:13:49,591
-What's burning?
-He's running around!

1759
01:13:49,658 --> 01:13:51,427
I'm seeing smoke.

1760
01:13:51,994 --> 01:13:53,228
The pan is smoking.

1761
01:13:54,229 --> 01:13:56,865
EDWARD QUICKLY STUFFS ICE INTO THE GLASS

1762
01:13:56,932 --> 01:13:59,301
-Ice?
-He got ice with his hands.

1763
01:13:59,368 --> 01:14:00,569
-Why?
-Edward looks flustered!

1764
01:14:00,636 --> 01:14:02,905
Wait, something is burning.

1765
01:14:02,971 --> 01:14:04,673
-Is this okay?
-I'm already done.

1766
01:14:04,740 --> 01:14:05,974
-You are?
-That was is done.

1767
01:14:06,041 --> 01:14:07,509
-That was done.
-Yes.

1768
01:14:07,576 --> 01:14:10,946
Now, the ragu is coming to a finish.
It was a bit runny before,

1769
01:14:11,013 --> 01:14:12,548
but it looks thicker now.

1770
01:14:12,614 --> 01:14:14,416
And the gnocchi are inside, right?

1771
01:14:14,483 --> 01:14:17,152
He's rolling them around in circles.

1772
01:14:17,219 --> 01:14:18,654
HE BEGINS TO SERVE

1773
01:14:18,720 --> 01:14:19,721
Is it done already?

1774
01:14:19,788 --> 01:14:22,458
-First, the gnocchi first.
-The gnocchi first.

1775
01:14:23,058 --> 01:14:25,260
THE FRESHLY MADE GNOCCHI
MADE IT OUT SAFELY

1776
01:14:25,327 --> 01:14:26,528
HE RUNS AGAIN!

1777
01:14:26,595 --> 01:14:28,063
Excuse me.

1778
01:14:29,431 --> 01:14:30,432
This is amazing.

1779
01:14:30,499 --> 01:14:33,068
-Eddy, why were you there?
-What did you get?

1780
01:14:33,135 --> 01:14:35,537
-He got a tomato.
-He stole a tomato?

1781
01:14:36,505 --> 01:14:38,440
1 SECOND
2 SECONDS

1782
01:14:38,507 --> 01:14:40,175
3 SECONDS
4 SECONDS

1783
01:14:40,242 --> 01:14:43,212
HOW IS KWON SUNG-JUN
FINISHING UP?

1784
01:14:43,278 --> 01:14:46,482
-The gnocchi is done.
-You have one minute left!

1785
01:14:46,548 --> 01:14:48,917
You have less than a minute left!
Please hurry!

1786
01:14:50,886 --> 01:14:53,889
11. TOP GNOCCHI WITH PERILLA LEAF
SALSA AND JULIENNED PERILLA LEAF

1787
01:14:53,956 --> 01:14:57,726
I'm seeing all kinds of things.
Eddy is now topping it with tomato.

1788
01:14:57,793 --> 01:14:59,027
He's using tomato.

1789
01:14:59,094 --> 01:15:00,929
11. TOP STEAK
WITH STEVIA CHERRY TOMATO

1790
01:15:01,497 --> 01:15:04,733
He's topping it
with the perilla leaf sauce.

1791
01:15:04,800 --> 01:15:06,902
-Hit the bell if you're done.
-Are you done?

1792
01:15:06,969 --> 01:15:08,537
-The steak is done.
-Hit the bell if you're done.

1793
01:15:08,604 --> 01:15:09,938
-Are you done?
-If you're done, hit it.

1794
01:15:10,005 --> 01:15:11,573
INTERCEPTS

1795
01:15:11,640 --> 01:15:14,643
-If you're done, hit it.
-He finishes first by a hair.

1796
01:15:14,710 --> 01:15:15,944
Kwon Sung-jun intercepts!

1797
01:15:16,011 --> 01:15:17,279
He was quick.

1798
01:15:17,346 --> 01:15:21,383
KWON SUNG-JUN MAKES HIS FINAL MOVE
BY INTERCEPTING

1799
01:15:21,450 --> 01:15:22,451
He was quick.

1800
01:15:22,518 --> 01:15:23,552
They're both done,

1801
01:15:24,353 --> 01:15:25,687
-leaving 30 seconds.
-They're done.

1802
01:15:25,754 --> 01:15:27,890
-They're both composed.
-They are.

1803
01:15:27,956 --> 01:15:28,957
It's over.

1804
01:15:29,024 --> 01:15:31,026
-Gosh, that's…
-Slowly.

1805
01:15:31,093 --> 01:15:34,229
They both finished cooking,
with just 30 seconds left.

1806
01:15:35,163 --> 01:15:37,733
-They're to die for.
-They are to die for.

1807
01:15:37,799 --> 01:15:39,635
THE PERILLA LEAF DISHES
ARE TO DIE FOR

1808
01:15:39,701 --> 01:15:43,772
I can't imagine
what this would taste like.

1809
01:15:43,839 --> 01:15:46,575
And now, the second round

1810
01:15:46,642 --> 01:15:49,278
with Suk-ku ingredients
finally comes to an end.

1811
01:15:49,344 --> 01:15:50,946
How was that match?

1812
01:15:51,013 --> 01:15:55,017
I love to watch artisans make things.

1813
01:15:55,083 --> 01:16:01,056
I believe artisans have a way
of making tough things look easy.

1814
01:16:01,123 --> 01:16:04,092
My mouth was dropped the whole time,
and I was speechless.

1815
01:16:04,159 --> 01:16:05,527
Another thing that came to me was that

1816
01:16:05,594 --> 01:16:07,896
<i>it was like watching</i>
<i>two gurus come together</i>

1817
01:16:08,463 --> 01:16:11,033
<i>to have a quiet yet bloody showdown.</i>

1818
01:16:11,099 --> 01:16:13,602
-It was thrilling.
-It was thrilling for him.

1819
01:16:13,669 --> 01:16:15,837
First, Chef Sung-jun.

1820
01:16:15,904 --> 01:16:20,008
He intercepted the bell
as Chef Eddy walked over.

1821
01:16:20,075 --> 01:16:21,577
-So quickly.
-Thank you.

1822
01:16:21,643 --> 01:16:23,779
Let's take a look at
Chef Sung-jun's dish first.

1823
01:16:23,845 --> 01:16:29,484
<i>Your Perilla Leaf Scent in the Gnocchi</i>

1824
01:16:30,986 --> 01:16:34,323
A PLATE OF MULTICULTURAL FLAVORS

1825
01:16:34,389 --> 01:16:38,160
CHEF KWON SUNG-JUN'S
YOUR PERILLA LEAF SCENT IN THE GNOCCHI

1826
01:16:38,727 --> 01:16:43,565
Gosh, this one.
He tops it with some perilla leaves.

1827
01:16:44,132 --> 01:16:46,068
-It's in the gnocchi too.
-He loves perilla leaves.

1828
01:16:46,134 --> 01:16:47,603
Yes, try the gnocchi too.

1829
01:16:47,669 --> 01:16:49,771
Does he smell perilla leaves?

1830
01:16:49,838 --> 01:16:51,940
It smells very exotic.

1831
01:16:52,007 --> 01:16:54,343
It already smells exotic.

1832
01:16:54,409 --> 01:16:57,746
Suk-ku said he liked butter and Thai food.

1833
01:16:59,281 --> 01:17:00,582
An art school cafeteria food…

1834
01:17:00,649 --> 01:17:02,417
SAVORING

1835
01:17:02,484 --> 01:17:05,587
-At the Art Institute of Chicago.
-The cafeteria food.

1836
01:17:08,957 --> 01:17:09,992
I wonder what it's like.

1837
01:17:10,058 --> 01:17:11,560
There are so many flavors.

1838
01:17:11,627 --> 01:17:14,062
-Many flavors.
-Yes.

1839
01:17:14,129 --> 01:17:16,465
I can finally smell the perilla leaf.

1840
01:17:16,531 --> 01:17:18,467
-It hits me last.
-I see.

1841
01:17:18,533 --> 01:17:19,601
It comes later.

1842
01:17:19,668 --> 01:17:21,603
The perilla leaf hits me at the end.

1843
01:17:21,670 --> 01:17:23,538
-Is it because it's the star?
-The perilla leaf.

1844
01:17:23,605 --> 01:17:25,540
-It hits me after ten seconds.
-Really?

1845
01:17:25,607 --> 01:17:26,808
I see.

1846
01:17:26,875 --> 01:17:28,977
The sauce has a strong flavor, right?

1847
01:17:29,044 --> 01:17:31,580
-It must be the strong sauce.
-The sauce is strong.

1848
01:17:31,647 --> 01:17:35,050
Although he tops it with perilla leaves,
it hits him much later.

1849
01:17:35,117 --> 01:17:37,386
He said he had many flavors.

1850
01:17:37,452 --> 01:17:41,256
He's frowning and searching for the taste.

1851
01:17:42,290 --> 01:17:43,492
What's this taste?

1852
01:17:43,558 --> 01:17:46,395
It doesn't feel like
I'm watching one movie.

1853
01:17:46,461 --> 01:17:48,664
It's like watching a series.

1854
01:17:48,730 --> 01:17:52,868
All kinds of international films go,
then lastly, the closer is a Korean film.

1855
01:17:52,934 --> 01:17:54,636
-Yes.
-I see.

1856
01:17:54,703 --> 01:17:56,371
The perilla leaf is the finale.

1857
01:17:56,438 --> 01:17:58,373
It's the finale. I see.

1858
01:17:58,440 --> 01:18:00,409
I honestly didn't know what gnocchi was.

1859
01:18:01,410 --> 01:18:02,844
It's good.

1860
01:18:02,911 --> 01:18:04,646
It has a fun texture.

1861
01:18:04,713 --> 01:18:06,281
-It does?
-Yes.

1862
01:18:06,348 --> 01:18:08,383
This will be so hard to choose.

1863
01:18:08,450 --> 01:18:10,652
-Thank you.
-This time, it's Chef Edward Lee.

1864
01:18:10,719 --> 01:18:13,155
Wrap More Beautiful Than Paradise.

1865
01:18:13,722 --> 01:18:16,425
I don't know what to expect.

1866
01:18:17,426 --> 01:18:20,662
CHEF EDWARD'S
WARP MORE BEAUTIFUL THAN PARADISE

1867
01:18:20,729 --> 01:18:23,098
It's a bit hard to explain,

1868
01:18:23,165 --> 01:18:25,033
so may I show it to you?

1869
01:18:25,100 --> 01:18:27,002
-Yes.
-He'll come himself.

1870
01:18:27,069 --> 01:18:28,804
He'll show him how to eat it.

1871
01:18:28,870 --> 01:18:31,506
He has to make the wrap,
so there must be an order.

1872
01:18:31,573 --> 01:18:35,010
The smell of the perilla leaf is
the most important.

1873
01:18:35,077 --> 01:18:38,246
So like wine, smell the leaves first.

1874
01:18:38,313 --> 01:18:42,084
-I see. It's like a diffuser.
-You can eat that too.

1875
01:18:42,150 --> 01:18:43,185
First, smell it.

1876
01:18:43,251 --> 01:18:44,586
Perilla leaf diffuser?

1877
01:18:46,221 --> 01:18:48,190
Put some on the wrap.

1878
01:18:48,790 --> 01:18:52,060
It got a little sticky after some time.

1879
01:18:52,127 --> 01:18:54,396
-I don't mind at all.
-Like this.

1880
01:18:54,463 --> 01:18:56,631
And a piece of meat.

1881
01:18:56,698 --> 01:18:57,733
A piece of meat.

1882
01:18:57,799 --> 01:18:59,668
-It's a peculiar mix.
-He's dipping it.

1883
01:18:59,735 --> 01:19:01,703
-And dip it.
-Dip it.

1884
01:19:01,770 --> 01:19:03,939
That's Wrap More Beautiful Than Paradise.

1885
01:19:04,005 --> 01:19:05,173
Yes, that's it.

1886
01:19:05,741 --> 01:19:07,509
All right, now.

1887
01:19:07,576 --> 01:19:08,877
I wonder what it's like.

1888
01:19:08,944 --> 01:19:10,779
-I'm so curious.
-Me too.

1889
01:19:10,846 --> 01:19:13,615
-I really wonder what it's like.
-That's… I can't imagine.

1890
01:19:13,682 --> 01:19:17,185
I was so honored to get the warp from him,
so I couldn't focus.

1891
01:19:17,252 --> 01:19:20,522
-Take your time to eat it.
-Take your time.

1892
01:19:20,589 --> 01:19:22,591
Make sure you separate it well.

1893
01:19:22,657 --> 01:19:25,060
-That's a lot.
-It's okay.

1894
01:19:25,127 --> 01:19:27,329
-Put in a lot.
-And two pieces of meat.

1895
01:19:27,395 --> 01:19:28,764
-Two pieces.
-That'll be a big wrap.

1896
01:19:28,830 --> 01:19:30,966
And two leaves, lots of noodles.

1897
01:19:31,032 --> 01:19:32,267
That sauce.

1898
01:19:32,334 --> 01:19:33,902
He put a lot of work into that sauce.

1899
01:19:33,969 --> 01:19:36,371
-The sauce had deep flavors.
-I see.

1900
01:19:36,438 --> 01:19:38,440
He took a big bite.

1901
01:19:39,608 --> 01:19:40,942
He doubled the wrap.

1902
01:19:42,878 --> 01:19:45,280
I wonder what it tastes like.

1903
01:19:45,347 --> 01:19:48,150
He looks very serious.

1904
01:19:48,216 --> 01:19:49,785
-Yes.
-Yes.

1905
01:19:50,786 --> 01:19:53,121
Tell us what it's like.
We're dying to know.

1906
01:19:53,188 --> 01:19:55,423
I think this is a flavor
I've never had before.

1907
01:19:55,490 --> 01:19:57,392
A NEW FLAVOR
WITH ORDINARY INGREDIENTS

1908
01:19:57,459 --> 01:19:59,661
I haven't seen you
this serious in a while.

1909
01:19:59,728 --> 01:20:00,729
Right?

1910
01:20:02,130 --> 01:20:04,199
I'm not sure.

1911
01:20:04,800 --> 01:20:07,569
It's good,
but I can't find a way to express this.

1912
01:20:08,203 --> 01:20:10,071
How is he going to express this?

1913
01:20:10,138 --> 01:20:12,808
It was a flavor you've never had before.

1914
01:20:13,508 --> 01:20:16,144
If I had to be technical,
it's Korean cuisine.

1915
01:20:16,211 --> 01:20:17,746
-Korean cuisine?
-It tastes like Korean cuisine?

1916
01:20:17,813 --> 01:20:20,382
It's like Korean cuisine.

1917
01:20:20,448 --> 01:20:23,485
It has many different flavors.

1918
01:20:23,552 --> 01:20:26,354
He added both ssamjang and kimchi.

1919
01:20:26,421 --> 01:20:28,824
-You have to try some too.
-Yes.

1920
01:20:28,890 --> 01:20:30,625
Try some. I need to think.

1921
01:20:30,692 --> 01:20:33,094
-Yes.
-He needs some time to think.

1922
01:20:33,161 --> 01:20:35,897
It was a flavor he has never had before.

1923
01:20:35,964 --> 01:20:38,033
Chef Sung-jun's dish first.

1924
01:20:38,533 --> 01:20:39,901
It smells so good.

1925
01:20:39,968 --> 01:20:41,636
-Does it already smell good?
-Yes.

1926
01:20:41,703 --> 01:20:42,771
THIS TIME, JUST THE NOODLES

1927
01:20:42,838 --> 01:20:45,273
He's savoring the taste.

1928
01:20:45,340 --> 01:20:47,676
He took a bite from Chef Sung-jun's dish.

1929
01:20:49,211 --> 01:20:51,513
Does it feel strange and unfamiliar?

1930
01:20:51,580 --> 01:20:55,250
-It's spectacular.
-"It's spectacular."

1931
01:20:55,317 --> 01:20:58,486
The world is a big place,
and there is so much good food.

1932
01:20:59,087 --> 01:21:03,024
I'm kind of sad today that I always eat

1933
01:21:03,091 --> 01:21:04,793
similar flavors.

1934
01:21:05,460 --> 01:21:06,962
Although there were dishes like these.

1935
01:21:07,028 --> 01:21:08,630
You've had this often, right?

1936
01:21:08,697 --> 01:21:10,765
I think I understand what you mean

1937
01:21:10,832 --> 01:21:12,767
by the Art Institute of Chicago.

1938
01:21:12,834 --> 01:21:14,135
Really?

1939
01:21:14,202 --> 01:21:15,303
I knew you'd notice.

1940
01:21:15,370 --> 01:21:16,771
You threw in cumin.

1941
01:21:16,838 --> 01:21:18,440
-Yes,
-Then, steak sauce.

1942
01:21:18,506 --> 01:21:21,576
It goes to the Middle East,
South America, Italy,

1943
01:21:21,643 --> 01:21:25,413
then in the end,
perilla leaves bring us back to Korea.

1944
01:21:25,480 --> 01:21:29,050
It's like how the school has students
from many different countries.

1945
01:21:29,117 --> 01:21:32,120
Now, Chef Eddy's dish.

1946
01:21:32,187 --> 01:21:35,056
-He has two leaves. One works as a dish.
-He's using two.

1947
01:21:35,123 --> 01:21:37,392
Poong has the most ordinary palate,

1948
01:21:38,326 --> 01:21:40,662
so I hope he draws
a simple picture for us.

1949
01:21:40,729 --> 01:21:41,897
My gosh.

1950
01:21:41,963 --> 01:21:44,933
Suk-ku keeps eating the dish
with his eyes closed.

1951
01:21:45,000 --> 01:21:47,535
Yes, this is
Wrap More Beautiful Than Paradise.

1952
01:21:48,703 --> 01:21:51,640
-Wrap works well with you.
-Yes, you have to eat it in one bite.

1953
01:21:51,706 --> 01:21:53,108
-It suits him.
-Yes.

1954
01:21:53,174 --> 01:21:55,977
-Chef Eddy's dish…
-Yes?

1955
01:21:56,044 --> 01:21:57,612
My tongue feels overjoyed.

1956
01:21:57,679 --> 01:22:00,148
-It's overjoyed?
-His tongue is overjoyed.

1957
01:22:00,215 --> 01:22:01,816
That was why you chewed for a while.

1958
01:22:01,883 --> 01:22:05,921
Chef Sung-jun's dish tasted exotic,
something I've never had before.

1959
01:22:05,987 --> 01:22:07,822
But this felt like my childhood,

1960
01:22:07,889 --> 01:22:10,792
when I took a short break
after helping out with the field work

1961
01:22:10,859 --> 01:22:15,196
in a cool shade in the middle of summer.

1962
01:22:17,432 --> 01:22:20,068
It reminds me of my hometown.

1963
01:22:20,135 --> 01:22:22,871
It must've made him feel safe.

1964
01:22:22,938 --> 01:22:25,507
I get why you said this was Korean.

1965
01:22:25,573 --> 01:22:29,177
-We also eat strong flavors like ssamjang.
-The flavor hits you.

1966
01:22:29,244 --> 01:22:32,447
<i>That kick is all in this sauce.</i>

1967
01:22:32,514 --> 01:22:34,316
But tastes so mild

1968
01:22:34,382 --> 01:22:37,419
and the texture isn't like Korean cuisine.

1969
01:22:37,485 --> 01:22:41,356
It's like the cold pasta
made with perilla leaf pesto.

1970
01:22:41,423 --> 01:22:42,991
It tastes like that pasta.

1971
01:22:43,058 --> 01:22:44,192
It's such a wonder.

1972
01:22:44,259 --> 01:22:46,027
It's Korean cuisine, yet it isn't.

1973
01:22:46,094 --> 01:22:50,432
-It's like deception, but in a good way.
-Yes.

1974
01:22:50,498 --> 01:22:53,468
If you eat a normal wrap
in Korean cuisine, it's like this.

1975
01:22:53,535 --> 01:22:56,538
And there's a certain flavor
you expect from these colors.

1976
01:22:56,604 --> 01:22:59,107
But something else hits you
instead of what you expect.

1977
01:22:59,174 --> 01:23:00,809
-I see.
-It's like that.

1978
01:23:00,875 --> 01:23:03,745
-It was two-faced.
-Yes.

1979
01:23:03,812 --> 01:23:07,449
-It's his turn to make the decision.
-I'm nervous.

1980
01:23:07,515 --> 01:23:10,452
That was a match between the top two
contestants of <i>Culinary Class Wars</i>.

1981
01:23:10,518 --> 01:23:12,921
Number one, Kwon Sung-jun.

1982
01:23:12,988 --> 01:23:15,156
Number two, Edward Lee.

1983
01:23:15,223 --> 01:23:17,192
Please press the button.

1984
01:23:18,426 --> 01:23:20,195
-I did.
-You did?

1985
01:23:20,261 --> 01:23:21,930
Yes, he pressed the button.

1986
01:23:21,997 --> 01:23:23,999
-All right.
-Round "Be perilla leaves."

1987
01:23:24,065 --> 01:23:25,500
-I'm nervous.
-So?

1988
01:23:25,567 --> 01:23:27,669
Will it be Kwon Sung-jun, the first place?

1989
01:23:27,736 --> 01:23:29,437
Or will it be Edward Lee,
the second place?

1990
01:23:29,504 --> 01:23:31,840
Will Kwon Sung-jun secure his throne?

1991
01:23:31,906 --> 01:23:34,009
Or will Edward Lee get his revenge?

1992
01:23:34,075 --> 01:23:37,445
Son Suk-ku is here to choose. Who won?

1993
01:23:37,512 --> 01:23:40,048
Show us the winner!

1994
01:23:40,115 --> 01:23:42,283
Who won?

1995
01:23:42,350 --> 01:23:43,351
The result is…

1996
01:23:44,352 --> 01:23:46,488
-The result is… Hey!
-Hey!

1997
01:23:46,554 --> 01:23:47,589
Kwon Sung-jun!

1998
01:23:48,156 --> 01:23:50,792
CHEF KWON SUNG-JUN WINS,
YOUR PERILLA LEAF SCENT IN THE GNOCCHI

1999
01:23:50,859 --> 01:23:52,427
Kwon Sung-jun wins.

2000
01:23:52,494 --> 01:23:54,429
Chef Sung-jun wins.

2001
01:23:57,132 --> 01:23:58,533
Chef Kwon Sung-jun.

2002
01:23:58,600 --> 01:24:03,071
He got to keep his title
as the winner of <i>Culinary Class Wars</i>.

2003
01:24:03,938 --> 01:24:06,474
I made the decision

2004
01:24:06,541 --> 01:24:10,211
because I had said
I wanted perilla leaves to be the star.

2005
01:24:10,278 --> 01:24:12,814
The gnocchi gave off

2006
01:24:12,881 --> 01:24:15,116
a strong perilla leaf flavor at the end.

2007
01:24:15,683 --> 01:24:18,286
-That was the most decisive.
-That decided it.

2008
01:24:18,353 --> 01:24:21,623
I began to wonder
if I couldn't smell the perilla leaf

2009
01:24:21,689 --> 01:24:22,757
because I had this first.

2010
01:24:22,824 --> 01:24:25,093
-I see.
-I see. This was too strong.

2011
01:24:25,160 --> 01:24:26,628
It was just as Suk-ku said.

2012
01:24:26,694 --> 01:24:29,064
I wanted to present my dish first.

2013
01:24:29,130 --> 01:24:32,033
If you taste this,
you won't taste anything else after that.

2014
01:24:32,100 --> 01:24:34,369
-That was your strategy?
-A bit.

2015
01:24:34,436 --> 01:24:36,071
-It was a strategic move.
-I knew it.

2016
01:24:36,137 --> 01:24:39,574
He barged in and got to the bell first.

2017
01:24:40,708 --> 01:24:43,111
-Edward got duped.
-He did.

2018
01:24:43,178 --> 01:24:45,313
We can't help it.
This is <i>Chef & My Fridge</i>.

2019
01:24:45,380 --> 01:24:46,848
Actually, starting around two minutes,

2020
01:24:46,915 --> 01:24:50,018
<i>I kept looking at Chef Edward's dish</i>
<i>instead of mine.</i>

2021
01:24:50,085 --> 01:24:52,587
-I see.
-You were sneaky.

2022
01:24:52,654 --> 01:24:54,589
This is

2023
01:24:54,656 --> 01:24:56,858
much harder than <i>Culinary Class Wars</i>.

2024
01:24:56,925 --> 01:24:59,160
STAY STRONG, KYUN, MY MAN

2025
01:25:00,795 --> 01:25:04,065
Please put the star on Chef Sung-jun!

2026
01:25:05,133 --> 01:25:08,203
Kwon Sung-jun finally wins a star
here on <i>Chef & My Fridge</i>!

2027
01:25:08,269 --> 01:25:10,738
Sung-jun's era finally begins.

2028
01:25:10,805 --> 01:25:12,874
-Thank you.
-Congratulations, Sung-jun!

2029
01:25:14,008 --> 01:25:15,944
When I first met Bong-sik,

2030
01:25:16,010 --> 01:25:17,712
he looked really intense.

2031
01:25:17,779 --> 01:25:19,881
-Right? He's scary.
-He looks scary.

2032
01:25:20,515 --> 01:25:21,516
CHUCKLE

2033
01:25:22,083 --> 01:25:23,818
WHAT? HE'S KIND OF CUTE

2034
01:25:23,885 --> 01:25:25,487
I'm totally lucky Bong-sik.

2035
01:25:25,553 --> 01:25:26,955
UNLIKE HOW HE LOOKS,
LUCKY BONG-SIK IS A CUTIE

2036
01:25:27,021 --> 01:25:28,223
You don't even drink?

2037
01:25:28,289 --> 01:25:29,557
-I couldn't.
-I see.

2038
01:25:29,624 --> 01:25:31,192
<i>You seemed like you'd chug on hard liquor.</i>

2039
01:25:31,259 --> 01:25:33,928
-How does it look, Detective Ahn?
-I think there is a bit of soju in here.

2040
01:25:33,995 --> 01:25:35,163
THE INVESTIGATORS
ARE GETTING CLOSER

2041
01:25:35,230 --> 01:25:38,833
-We got him. We got Bong-sik.
-These are soju.

2042
01:25:38,900 --> 01:25:40,335
-Why do you keep these?
-Wait.

2043
01:25:40,401 --> 01:25:42,137
WHAT IS THE TRUTH?

2044
01:25:42,203 --> 01:25:44,806
<i>I'll show him</i>
<i>how spicy </i>Chef & My Fridge<i> can be.</i>

2045
01:25:44,873 --> 01:25:45,874
<i>Yes, you should.</i>

2046
01:25:45,940 --> 01:25:48,109
<i>I'll become a killer today.</i>

2047
01:25:48,176 --> 01:25:49,377
<i>That means he won't lose.</i>

2048
01:25:49,444 --> 01:25:51,546
<i>They face this deadly match</i>
<i>at the edge of their demise!</i>

2049
01:25:51,613 --> 01:25:53,148
<i>I'm not scared of losing.</i>

2050
01:25:53,214 --> 01:25:54,582
<i>-Like this?</i>
<i>-Yes.</i>

2051
01:25:54,649 --> 01:25:55,850
<i>It feels like the holidays.</i>

2052
01:25:55,917 --> 01:25:58,253
-What's wrong?
-What's wrong?

2053
01:25:58,319 --> 01:25:59,821
He's on fire!

2054
01:25:59,888 --> 01:26:01,689
-What's wrong with this?
-What now?

2055
01:26:01,756 --> 01:26:03,858
-You still have time!
-This is crazy!

2056
01:26:03,925 --> 01:26:05,160
Why didn't you tell me sooner?

2057
01:26:05,226 --> 01:26:06,761
<i>-Seriously!</i>
<i>-Oh, no!</i>

2058
01:26:07,929 --> 01:26:09,464
Wait, what are you two doing right now?

2059
01:26:09,531 --> 01:26:11,900
-We're on a date.
-A date?

2060
01:26:11,966 --> 01:26:14,402
-We won't bother you.
-No.

2061
01:26:23,478 --> 01:26:28,483
Subtitle translation by: Eunsook Youn
